comments.text:
Thank you for sharing this video. I am a Pashtoon woman from a very remote area in Afghanistan. Women in Afghanistan are not as they are often portrayed on TV—they have many rights. However, I am deeply saddened that schools have been closed. The main issue is that the country has been left in darkness for decades due to war. While people read the Quran, many do not understand its meaning because it is written in Arabic, and there is no education system in many villages. Even during the 20 years of war when Americans were present, many villagers would go to the Taliban for decisions rather than government courts. This reflects how simple and illiterate people are in some areas. Additionally, most Pashtoons follow their own code of conduct, Pashtoonwali, which is a rule of life in itself, though it may differ from formal systems.
Every country has its own up and down. But we Afghans have honor and beautiful cultures. Woman is protected man will destroy a whole village for a woman if anyone even look at her in bad way or even say word. So every country has its own unique culture and rules.
